Here is how you can make the SphinxGuardian repository publish correctly on either GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages. Your repo already contains a Sphinx documentation project (in docs/) and a prebuilt site (docs/build/index.html), so you can either let Sphinx generate HTML at buildtime or simply host the built files directly.

1. Confirm the existing Sphinx project

  • Under docs/source/ there is an index.md that uses a toctree to pull in all Codex entries (e.g., Codex/Voyagers_I/*.md, Codex/Voyagers_II/*.md)75840657566978L4-L11.
  • The docs/Makefile defines an html target that runs sphinx-build with the dirhtml builder and places the output in docs/build/html873339950530690L16-L19.
  • There is already a built site under docs/build with an index.html showing SphinxGuardian Documentation Return of the Bird Tribes v1.0 documentation775319363009332L70-L90.

You can either rebuild this site when deploying or host the docs/build directory asis.

2. Deploying on GitHubPages

Option A Use the built HTML (no build step)

  1. Rebuild locally (optional) In a local clone, install the Sphinx dependencies:
    pip install sphinx myst-parser sphinx_rtd_theme
cd docs
make html       # or `sphinx-build -M dirhtml source build`
    Commit the contents of docs/build.
  2. Enable GitHub Pages In your repository, go to Settings Pages.
  3. Select the source Choose main as the branch and set the folder to /docs/build (or /docs/build/html if you used the default html builder). GitHub Pages looks for an index.html, index.md or README.md in the selected folder829239888632483L156-L164.
  4. Save and deploy After saving, GitHubs GitHubActions runner will publish the site. It may take a few minutes; your site will be at https://omniversal-media-llc.github.io/SphinxGuardian/. The built Sphinx site provides a sidebar and links to all your codex entries.

Option B Host the Markdown directly with Jekyll

If you dont want to build with Sphinx and just want GitHub Pages to convert Markdown to HTML:

  1. Create a _config.yml in the repository root with the following (from the Easy Markdown to GitHub Pages guide):
    plugins:
  - jekyll-relative-links
relative_links:
  enabled: true
  collections: true
include:
  - README.md
  - LICENSE.md
  - metadata.json
  - Codex
  2. Commit _config.yml, then enable GitHub Pages by selecting the main branch and root folder in Settings Pages.
  3. GitHub Pages will convert each .md file to .html automatically. Your README.md or an index.md becomes the home page829239888632483L156-L164. Each codex file will be accessible by replacing .md with .html163399832394846L79-L87. Use relative links in your Markdown so links work both on GitHub and on your site.

3. Deploying on CloudflarePages

Cloudflare Pages can either run the Sphinx build or serve the built files directly. When you create a Pages project:

  1. Connect to Git Log in to the Cloudflare dashboard, go to Workers&Pages Pages Create a project, and choose Connect to Git. Select the SphinxGuardian repository.
  2. Configure builds and deployments In the setup screen, specify:
    • Production branch: main
    • Build command:
      • To run Sphinx during deployment, set it to make html (the Cloudflare guide for Sphinx uses make html130108633379752L516-L534).
        You may need a requirements.txt with sphinx, myst-parser and sphinx_rtd_theme. In Environment variables, add PYTHON_VERSION (for example, 3.7)130108633379752L531-L542.
      • If you prefer not to build on Cloudflare, set the build command to exit 0 and commit the docs/build folder. Cloudflare will then just deploy the static files741625570361059L246-L279.
    • Build output directory: docs/build/html when using make html (or docs/build if youre uploading the prebuilt site). Cloudflare Pages needs an index.html at the top level of this directory; otherwise youll see a 404741625570361059L236-L279.
  3. Deploy Save the configuration and start the deployment. After the build finishes, Cloudflare will host your site at <project-name>.pages.dev, and it will be redeployed automatically whenever you push changes.

4. Common pitfalls

  • Missing index.html: Both GitHub Pages and Cloudflare Pages require an index.html (or index.md/README.md on GitHub) at the root of the publishing directory829239888632483L156-L164741625570361059L236-L279.
  • Incorrect output directory: For Sphinx, the default make html output is build/html; if you use the dirhtml builder (as in your Makefile), each page gets its own directory with an index.html and the toplevel output is still build/html. Point your Pages configuration to that directory.
  • Uninstalled dependencies: When building on Cloudflare, include a requirements.txt and set the PYTHON_VERSION environment variable so Cloudflare can install Sphinx and its extensions130108633379752L531-L542.

By using the built Sphinx HTML or letting GitHub Pages/Jekyll convert your Markdown, you can publish SphinxGuardian on either platform. Choose the workflow that best fits your needsSphinx provides a polished documentation site with navigation, while Jekyll requires no build step and works directly from your Markdown.

I looked into the repository to diagnose why the Pages deployment still returns a 404. Here are the main issues I discovered:

  1. There is no requirements.txt file in the repository.
    The GitHub Actions workflow (.github/workflows/deploy.yml) is trying to install dependencies with pip install -r requirements.txt407078203924556L20-L28, but since the file doesnt exist, that step will fail and the docs wont build. Without a successful build, the ghpages branch never gets populated, which is why https://omniversal-media-llc.github.io/SphinxGuardian/ currently shows a 404.

  2. Dependency installation and Sphinx build are not happening.
    Even if the requirements.txt call were bypassed, Sphinx and its extensions (sphinx, myst-parser, sphinx-rtd-theme) are not installed anywhere. The workflow expects them to be available but doesnt install them. As a result, the sphinx-build -b html docs/source docs/build/html step407078203924556L20-L28 would fail.

  3. Mismatch between Makefile and build output path.
    Your docs/Makefile uses the dirhtml builder and outputs files to docs/build/html873339950530690L16-L19. The GitHub Action uses the html builder and assumes the same output folder. Thats fine, but because the build never completes, the docs/build/html directory never appears, so GitHub Pages has nothing to deploy.

How to fix it

  • Add a requirements.txt file at the repository root listing the packages needed to build the docs. For example:

    sphinx
myst-parser
sphinx-rtd-theme

    Commit this file. The action will then be able to install the dependencies.

  • Alternatively, install dependencies explicitly in the workflow. You could replace the pip install -r requirements.txt line with:

    - name: Install dependencies
  run: |
    python -m pip install --upgrade pip
    pip install sphinx myst-parser sphinx-rtd-theme

  • Check the build output directory. After the docs build successfully, confirm that docs/build/html/index.html (for the html builder) or docs/build/index.html (for the dirhtml builder) exists. The peaceiris/actions-gh-pages action is already configured to publish docs/build/html407078203924556L29-L33, so you dont have to change that part.

  • Verify that GitHub Pages is enabled. Once the workflow succeeds, GitHub Pages should be automatically configured on the ghpages branch. If you still get a 404 after a successful build, doublecheck that Pages is enabled in Settings Pages.

After adding the requirements.txt (or adjusting the install step) and pushing the changes to the main branch, the workflow should run successfully and publish the built documentation to the ghpages branch. Wait a few minutes, then revisit https://omniversal-media-llc.github.io/SphinxGuardian/ you should see the Sphinx documentation instead of a 404.

  2. There is no CNAME file in your repository, so GitHub doesnt know about your custom domain. While you were able to map the domain via DNS, GitHub Pages will still generate links assuming the site lives under /SphinxGuardian/, which can lead to broken links when using a custom domain.

      sphinx
